<p>Born in Hong Kong, Danny, Li Wan Fai learned western painting in the late &lsquo;60s from Chiang Wing-sin, an established oil painter from China. His continuous experimentations with different techniques led him to develop his individualistic style. In 1984, Li&rsquo;s debut solo exhibition in Royce Gallery, Sydney, Australia brought him recognition.&nbsp; His work was selected for the XXI and the XXII Prix International D&rsquo;Art Contemporain de Monte-Carlo in 1987 and 1988.&nbsp; He also participated in the Contemporary Hong Kong Art Biennial from 1985 to 1996.<br>
<br>
On this canvas, Li renders the famous lion&rsquo;s head rock formation, a natural landmark of Hong Kong, with his unique style of heavy brushstrokes for texture, and brilliant colour tones for depth and space.&nbsp; He contrasts the dense vegetation with the craggy peak and enlivens the barren Lion&rsquo;s Rock with an air of regality.&nbsp; The work reveals a crouching lion contemplating intensely under the azure blue sky.&nbsp; The work evokes a man&rsquo;s respect for the stillness and vitality of the untamed nature. <br>
<br>
Hongkong Land commissioned the &ldquo;The Lion&rsquo;s Rock Under the Summer Sky&rdquo; in 2012.&nbsp;</p>
<br>
